#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""gdvb-lsp-graph - emit a symbol call graph from a language server, as JSON.

A standalone LSP CLIENT for the gdvb viewer: it speaks JSON-RPC over an
already-connected duplex byte stream to WHATEVER language server is on the other
end, walks the CALL HIERARCHY outward from one or more seed symbols, and prints
ONE JSON graph model to stdout - the same generic model the other generators
produce. It does NOT import gdvb-render; the JSON model is the only
contract.

gdvb-lsp-graph does not know how to start a language server, and deliberately so: LSP
only specifies the JSON-RPC message protocol, not a transport - servers each pick
their own (stdio-only, a TCP/Unix socket, node-ipc, ...), and getting one running
with the right flags (a C++ project's compile_commands.json, a Python venv, ...)
is a different problem from turning its responses into a graph. That's the job of
a per-server GENERATOR wrapper (e.g. `gdvb-clangd-lsp-graph`, `gdvb-pyright-lsp-graph`):
each spins up its server, bridges it to a Unix domain socket, and calls this with
--connect pointed at it - gdvb-lsp-graph itself never spawns a process. Use those
wrappers directly; only reach for gdvb-lsp-graph --connect yourself if you already have
a server listening on a socket some other way.

    gdvb-clangd-lsp-graph <project> --file src/foo.cpp | gdvb-render > calls.html
    gdvb-pyright-lsp-graph <project> --all --max-nodes 5000 | gdvb-render > c.html
    gdvb-lsp-graph <project> --connect /tmp/lsp.sock --seed planPath   # low-level, direct

The graph is built from `callHierarchy/incomingCalls` (who calls X) by default,
walking UP the call graph from the seeds - the impact-analysis direction ("what
breaks if I change this"). Edges are directed caller->callee, so the viewer
navigates either way. `--direction out`/`both` also walks `outgoingCalls` for
servers that implement it (clangd 14 doesn't - it always returns empty there, a
harmless no-op; pyright implements both directions fully).

Every method/constructor discovered also pulls in its OWNING TYPE (class/struct/
interface/enum) as a first-class node, via `textDocument/documentSymbol`
containment - a `member-of` edge from the callable to its type. Each type then
resolves its ancestors/descendants via typeHierarchy into `inherits` edges
(derived->base), bounded by `--type-depth` hops - tried via the standardized LSP
3.17 prepareTypeHierarchy/supertypes/subtypes trio first, falling back to
clangd's older pre-standardization extension; skipped entirely if the server
never advertised typeHierarchyProvider at all (e.g. pyright, which only
implements call hierarchy).

`--all` seeds from every function/type in the project instead of a specific
--seed/--file: it walks every source file under the project root (documentSymbol,
not e.g. a C++ compile_commands.json's TU list, since headers - where most
classes live - aren't their own translation unit) and adds every callable/type it
finds, without the `seed` border (marking everything "the seed" is meaningless).
Combine with a larger --max-nodes; the default (400) truncates quickly on a whole
project. Source-file discovery is by extension (see LANG_BY_EXT) plus a shebang
sniff for extensionless scripts (this project's own convention).

Stdlib only.
"""
import os
import sys
import json
import time
import select
import socket
import argparse
